# pgbouncer/userlist.txt.example — TEMPLATE ONLY
#
# DO NOT use plaintext passwords in production.  This file must be copied to
# pgbouncer/userlist.txt (which is git-ignored) and populated with a real
# SCRAM-SHA-256 hashed password before deploying pgbouncer.
#
# HOW TO GENERATE A SCRAM-SHA-256 HASH
# =====================================
# 1. Connect to your PostgreSQL instance as a superuser:
#      psql -U postgres -d conclave
#
# 2. Create or alter the user with a password so PostgreSQL stores the hash:
#      ALTER USER synth_user WITH PASSWORD 'your-strong-password-here';
#
# 3. Extract the stored SCRAM-SHA-256 hash:
#      SELECT concat('"', usename, '" "', passwd, '"')
#      FROM   pg_shadow
#      WHERE  usename = 'synth_user';
#
# 4. Copy the output line (it will look like the placeholder below) into
#    pgbouncer/userlist.txt — not this example file.
#
# FORMAT
# ======
# Each line: "username" "SCRAM-SHA-256$<iterations>:<salt>$<storedkey>:<serverkey>"
# Example (replace with your real hash):
#
# "synth_user" "SCRAM-SHA-256$4096:AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA$BBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBB:CCCCCCCCCCCCCCCCCCCCCCCCCCCCCCCCCCCCCCCCCCCC"
#
# OPERATOR CHECKLIST (before first docker-compose up)
# =====================================================
# [ ] Copy this file:  cp pgbouncer/userlist.txt.example pgbouncer/userlist.txt
# [ ] Replace the placeholder hash with the real SCRAM-SHA-256 output from pg_shadow
# [ ] Verify pgbouncer/userlist.txt is NOT staged:  git status pgbouncer/userlist.txt
# [ ] chmod 600 pgbouncer/userlist.txt
